          "explanation": "Complications of Colle's fracture :\n\nComplications in college's fracture are high (50 - 60%). Following complications may occur\n\n1) The stiffness of fingers and joints :\n\nThe stiffness of finger, wrist and shoulder is the most common avoidable complication of Colle's fracture.\n\n2) Malunion :\n\nIt is the second most common complication.\nIt results in dinner fork deformity.\n\n\nSudek's osteodystrophy (reflex sympathetic dystrophy).\nCarpal tunnel syndrome.\nCarpal instability.\nRupture of the extensor pollicis longus tendon.\nFrozen shoulder syndrome.\nTFCC injury.\nNon - union is very rare."
