          "explanation": "This child has : -\n\n\nFracture around elbow\nTingling and numbness in ulnar nerve distribution after 4 years.\n\n\nThat means the child has developed tardy ulnar nerve palsy (late onset ulnar nerve palsy).\nNow you must be thinking option 'a, b & d' all can cause tardy ulnar nerve palsy, then why the answer is '13'.\nHere the age of the child, at the time of fracture, is 6 years.\nElbow dislocation occurs usually in adults and uncommon in children.\nThe age matches with both supracondylar fracture (5-7 years) and fracture lateral condyle (5-10 years).\nHowever, Tardy ulnar nerve palsy is more common in malunited fracture lateral condyle (cubitus valgus) and occurs only occasionally in malunited supracondylar fracture (cubitus varus).\nTherefore, answer of choice here is fracture lateral condyle humerus."
