          "correctOptionId": "opt-1",
          "explanation": "In a bilateral dislocation the gait is described as 'duck like waddle' or 'sailor's gait and consists of an inclination to the side on which the weight is born (lurching gait on both side). In unilateral cases the child lurches towards affected side. This is known as abductor lurch or Trendelenburg gait.\n\n\nLordosis is particularly noticeable in bilateral cases & is often presenting complaint.\n\n\nThere short stature with both lower limbs appear too short for the body.\nThere is compensatory genu valgum. As both hips are adducted patient tries to keep the feet outside, which causes bilateral compensatory genu valgum.\n\n\nShenton's line is broken."
